In a #medium bowl{}, toss together @coleslaw mix{4%ounce}, @white wine vinegar{5%teaspoon}, a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon}, and @sugar{1%teaspoon}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}; set aside.

Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}. In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, @hot sauce{1%teaspoon} to taste, and a large pinch of @salt{}. Stir in water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add onion and cook, stirring, until just softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

While onion cooks, tear @pulled pork{10%ounce} into smaller pieces. Add to same pan along with another drizzle of oil. Season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon}. Cook, stirring, until pork is warmed through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in @tomato paste{1.5%ounce} to coat, then add @chicken stock concentrate{1} and @water{1/2%cup}. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low. Simmer until mixture is saucy, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn off heat.

Meanwhile, wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}. 

> Alternatively, wrap tortillas in foil and warm in a 425 degree oven for 5 minutes.

Divide pork filling between tortillas. Top with slaw and drizzle with crema. Serve.

> TIP: You may have extra pork filling—if so, serve it on the side.